## A niche is a habitat that a species can live in, and the role it plays in that habitat



### Every species has a range of *factors* that influence which niches they are able to occupy 
- Types of factors:
	- Physiological tolerances
		- The range of conditions that an organism's body can function in
		- Many paramaters, such as:
			- Temperature
			- Water requirements
			- Light requirements
	- Resource needs
		- Generally food
		- Abiotic and biotic constraints
	- Species interactions
		- IE [[Unsorted/Communities\|predation]], [[Unsorted/Communities\|mutualism]]

- These factors all have a range of tolerance
	- Optimal range (Species abundant)
	- Zone of physiological distress (Species infrequent)
	- Zone of intolerance (Species absent)
	- ![Pasted image 20220927182552.png](data:image/png;base64,)
- Niches are n-dimensional
	- There's no limit to the number of factors that can be involved
- 

## Examples
- Squirrel
	- Needs a low concentration of predators
	- High concentration of oak trees
		- For acorns, their main food source
	- Burrow availability
		- Need to be able to store food and hide from predators
	- All of these factors contribute to an organism's successfulness in a given environment





## Types of roles
- Generalists
	- IE
		- Raccoons, beetles, etc
- Highly-specialized
	- Much more susceptible to environmental chaos
	- IE
		- Birds with specialized beaks for their particular food source
	- Different ecological tolerances
		- Heat, water, light, etc




## Competition
- Competition is the relationship that occurs when multiple organisms seek the same limited resources
	- Two [[Unsorted/Species\|species]] that occupy the same niche (compete for the same limited resources) cannot coexist indefinitely
		- One will eventually be pushed out because one is better suited than the other
	- When one of the organisms are less suited to a niche than their competitor, there is significant pressure for them to seek alternative sources of essential resources, and thus a new niche
	- This also results in resource partitioning:
		- ...the process through which different species will specialize in different forms of a particular limited resource they all need in order to avoid competition 
- Large populations of a single [[Unsorted/Species\|species]] can experience [[Unsorted/Evolution\|speciation]], which has similar properties to competition
	- eg. A large population at or above the carrying capacity of their niche
	- Individuals have variations in their abilities
		- They have ideal resource sources
		- ..but can specialize to get better at acquiring alternative sources
